e stored together with the survey data, will only be used to inform you of the raffle outcome and will be deleted directly after the study is finished. The data collected may be used for scientific publication but can never be traced back to you personally. The anonymous research data can be accessed by the principal investigator (Thomas Reijnders), the involved PhD-candidate (David de Buisonjé) and students working on their Bachelor thesis in this project.     Contact  If you have questions at any time about the study or the procedures, you may contact the conductor of this research, David de Buisonjé via email at d.r.de.buisonje@fsw.leidenuniv.nl. You may also contact the principal investigator of this study, Thomas Reijnders, via email at t.reijnders@fsw.leidenuniv.nl or by phone: +31 71 527 2727. If you feel you have not been treated according to the descriptions in this form, or that your rights as a participant in research have not been honoured during the course of this project, or you have any questions, concerns, or complaints that you wish to address to someone other than the investigators, you may contact Dr. Veronica Janssen via email at vjanssen@fsw.leidenuniv.nl. You may also contact the privacy officer at the Faculty of Social sciences Drs Raymond van Erkel via email at r.van.erkel@fsw.leidenuniv.nl.      Please select your choice below. You may print a copy of this consent form for your records. Clicking on the “Agree” button indicates that:     - You have read the above information  - You voluntarily agree to participate  - You are 18 years of age or older  - You can read and understand the English language good enough to participate in this study ; Thank you. This is the end of the study.  The aim of this study was to better understand what the effects are of different forms of financial incentives for health behavior change.   You were randomly offered one of five possible conditions. Firstly, some of you were assigned to a control condition in which you only set a goal and received feedback about your progress. Additionally, in four experimental conditions we added different forms of financial incentives to this basic control condition: (1) an incentive where money could be gained with positive feedback about your earnings, (2) an incentive where money could be gained with negative feedback about your losses, (3) an incentive where money had to be deposited first and could then be regained with positive feedback about your earnings or (4) an incentive where money had to be deposited first and could then beregained with negative feedback about your losses.   We did not mention this in so much detail in the information letter, to be sure that your possible knowledge about this research could not influence your answers and thereby influence what we tried to learn.  If you were assigned to one of the financial incentive conditions where we asked for a personal deposit, there was an additional element of deception which we will now explain. Because we wanted to investigate the effect of possibly losing some of your own money, we informed you that (part of) your personal deposit could be lost based on your daily steps goal achievement. However, because we want to minimize the risk of financial damage we will refund the entire deposit for all participants. We did not mention this before or during the experiment because that would eliminate the motivating potential of this possible loss.   Your contribution to this research is important because we can learn more about what incentive programs may be effective to support healthy living. This allows us to develop effective incentive programs that can be added to interventions in order to support a healthy lifestyle.   If you want to continue to work on your lifestyle, you can continue using the Google Fit or Apple Health app that you have downloaded on your phone to track your physical activity.   If you have any questions about your medical situation we advise you to talk to your general practitioner for professional advice.  If you have any questions, or would like to know more about this research, please contact David de Buisonjé at the following e-mail address: d.r.de.buisonje@fsw.leidenuniv.nl.   You may also contact the principal investigator of this study, Thomas Reijnders, via email at t.reijnders@fsw.leidenuniv.nl or by phone: +31 71 527 2727.  We have recorded you response and you can close the window now.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    ; Group time: ; Group time: .1; Group time: .2; Group time: .3; Group time: .4; Group time: .5; Group time: .6; Group time: End page; Why did you want to participate in our study at first? (multiple answers possible) [I wanted to get a reward for my physical activity]; What was your reason to not continue with the study when you were asked for a deposit? (multiple answers possible) [The deposit amount was too high]; What was your reason to not continue with the study when you were asked for a deposit? (multiple answers possible) [The payment method did not work]; What was your reason to not continue with the study when you were asked for a deposit? (multiple answers possible) [I did not want to risk losing my deposit]; What was your reason to not continue with the study when you were asked for a deposit? (multiple answers possible) [The step goal was too high and I did not think I could make it]; What was your reason to not continue with the study when you were asked for a deposit? (multiple answers possible) [The current Corona situation had an impact on my decision ]; What was your reason to not continue with the study when you were asked for a deposit? (multiple answers possible) [Ethical/moral reasons (like objections to use money for motivation) ]; What was 